      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#191817;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Damage and liability during Brisbane open homes: what sellers should know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(25,24,23,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Theft gets all the attention, but the more common open-home issue is something getting broken, a child running into a glass door, or a visitor slipping on a wet step. The rules of who pays and who is liable are not what most sellers assume.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most conversations about open-home risk start and end with theft. The bigger and more frequent issue across a Brisbane campaign is actually accidental damage and visitor injury. A child knocks over a vase. A toddler runs into a frameless glass shower screen. A visitor in heels slips on a freshly mopped tile floor at the entry. A small dog the owner forgot to mention nips a buyer's calf. None of these are theatrical. All of them happen across a normal selling season in the inner east, and almost all of them are preventable with thirty minutes of preparation and a clear understanding of how liability actually works.</p>

      <p>The questions sellers usually ask are: who pays if something is broken, who is liable if someone is hurt, and what does my home insurance actually cover during a sale campaign. The answers are more useful than most people expect, but they depend on a few practical details that are worth getting right before the first open home.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The damage that actually happens at open homes</h2>

      <p>Across a typical four-week Brisbane campaign with eight open homes and a handful of midweek inspections, you can expect roughly one to three minor incidents. The pattern is consistent year after year.</p>

      <p>Knocked items: vases, ornaments, photo frames, small sculptures on side tables. The home is often busier during an open home than at any other time of the year, and visitors moving through narrow corridors with children, prams or bags create a low but steady risk of bumping a side table or shelf. The damage is rarely large in dollar terms but can be high in sentimental value.</p>

      <p>Wall and skirting marks: bags, belts, buckles and pram wheels brush along walls and corners. White or pale walls in narrow hallways show every contact. The cost of a touch-up is low, but the visual impact during the campaign can be significant if it builds up across multiple inspections.</p>

      <p>Floor damage: stiletto heels on soft timber, gritty shoe soles on light carpet, a buyer's child with juice or coffee. Brisbane summer storms produce a particular version of this where every visitor in a thirty-minute window walks in with wet shoes onto a polished timber floor. The damage is usually minor but can be cumulative.</p>

      <p>Bathroom and kitchen fixture damage: shower screens nudged when a buyer leans on them, toilet seats and cisterns tested with curiosity, oven door handles pulled too hard, drawer fronts and cupboard hinges stressed by visitors who open every storage space. None of these is a major fault, but loose hinges and small chips on the lip of a stone bench are a familiar pattern after a busy weekend.</p>

      <p>Garden and outdoor damage: pavers chipped by heavy shoes, garden beds trodden on by buyers walking the boundary, gate latches stressed by visitors who let themselves in and out repeatedly through the campaign. Outdoor areas tend to take more wear than sellers expect because the inspection is often less supervised outside than inside.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who pays when something is broken</h2>

      <p>The starting point under Queensland law is that whoever causes the damage is responsible for it. If a visitor knocks a vase off a side table, the visitor is responsible for the cost. In practice, that legal position is hard to enforce because the visitor has often left before the damage is discovered, and pursuing a small claim against a stranger named on a sign-in sheet is rarely worth the time or the friction.</p>

      <p>The agent is not automatically liable for damage caused by a visitor unless the agent was negligent in supervising the inspection. If two staff were on site, the visitor was signed in, and the damage occurred while the visitor was being reasonably supervised, the agent has not breached their duty of care to the seller.</p>

      <p>The seller's home and contents insurance is the practical fallback. Most policies cover accidental damage to contents during an inspection, but only where the policy includes accidental damage cover, which is not always included by default. The standard "fire, theft and storm" cover does not extend to a vase being knocked off a table during an open home. Adding accidental damage cover for the duration of the campaign is usually inexpensive and removes the most common practical risk.</p>

      <p>Higher-value items follow the same logic but require attention to specified-item limits. A $4,000 ceramic on the entry table is technically covered under contents accidental damage in many policies, but the policy may have a $1,000 single-item limit unless the item has been specified separately. A short call to your insurer before the campaign confirms which items need to be itemised and which are covered under the general contents sum insured.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Visitor injury and public liability</h2>

      <p>Property damage is the common case. Visitor injury is the rarer but higher-stakes case. The classic open-home injury scenarios are a slip on a wet entry tile, a trip on an uneven step, a child running into a frameless glass shower screen or sliding door, and a guest knocking their head on a low beam in a renovated cottage where the ceiling height changes mid-room.</p>

      <p>The legal framework is occupier's liability under Queensland law. As the owner of the property you have a duty of care to anyone who is lawfully on the premises. That duty is to take reasonable steps to identify and address hazards that could foreseeably cause injury. The standard is "reasonable", not "perfect". You are not expected to eliminate every conceivable risk, but you are expected to act on hazards you know about or that a reasonable owner would identify.</p>

      <p>Home insurance policies in Queensland generally include public liability cover as part of the home buildings policy. The typical sum insured is $20 million, which is more than enough for almost any open-home injury claim. The cover applies to visitors who are lawfully on the property and who are injured as a result of the property's condition. That is the right structure for an open home: inspectors are lawful visitors, and a slip on a wet step is a property-condition incident.</p>

      <p>The condition that matters is whether you took reasonable steps to prevent the harm. If a step has been broken for three months and you knew about it but did not fix or flag it, that materially weakens the position. If the step was sound, the floor was dry, the warning was clear, and the injury occurred because the visitor was inattentive, the insurance position is straightforward.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The hazards Brisbane sellers should address before the first open home</h2>

      <p>The walkthrough below takes about thirty minutes and addresses the hazards that show up in actual claims.</p>

      <p>Wet entries during summer storms: Brisbane's storm season produces wet tile and timber entries with very short notice. A rubber-backed mat at the entry, a stack of clean towels available for the agent, and a habit of mopping the entry between groups of visitors prevents the most common slip scenario.</p>

      <p>Uneven steps, missing rails, and edge transitions: the steps from a verandah into a back garden, from a kitchen to a sunken living room, from a hallway into a bathroom. If a step is uneven by more than a few centimetres or if there is no contrast strip on the edge, that is the kind of feature that catches a visitor focused on the property rather than on their feet. A bright tape strip, a small sign, or a temporary handrail is a low-cost fix for the duration of the campaign.</p>

      <p>Frameless glass and full-height glass doors: a known hazard for children and for adults who are looking at the view rather than the door. Small adhesive frosted-glass dots or vinyl decals at adult and child eye height eliminate the issue. These can be removed at the end of the campaign with no residue.</p>

      <p>Low beams in renovated cottages: a particular Brisbane character home issue where a renovation has produced a transition between rooms with a beam at head height for taller visitors. A discreet contrast paint on the beam edge or a small "mind your head" sign at the threshold addresses the risk without disturbing the aesthetic.</p>

      <p>Loose pavers, lifted edges of outdoor tiling, exposed root systems in the garden: outdoor inspections are the most common injury scenario because visitors walk the boundary with their eyes on the property. Walk the outdoor path with fresh eyes the day before the first open home and address any edge that is more than a couple of centimetres higher than the surrounding surface.</p>

      <p>Pool fencing and pool gate self-closing mechanisms: if the property has a pool, the inspection is the worst possible time for a self-closing gate to fail. A quick test the morning of every open home that the gate latches without manual help is a standard pool-property routine in Brisbane. A failing latch on inspection day with children on site is the highest-risk scenario in this whole article.</p>

      <p>Pets: dogs and cats should be removed from the property for the duration of every open home. Even a calm, well-trained dog can react unpredictably to twenty strangers moving through the home in a thirty-minute window. A bite, a knockdown of a small child, or a visitor with a phobia having a panic reaction are all preventable by having pets off-site. This is also a marketing point: visitors should be focused on the property, not managing their reaction to an unfamiliar animal.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to document before the first open home</h2>

      <p>The documentation that supports a claim is straightforward and takes about fifteen minutes the day before the first inspection.</p>

      <p>Walkthrough photographs: a clear photo of the entry, the main rooms, the bathrooms, and the outdoor areas as they look in their final pre-inspection condition. These establish the baseline if a claim is later needed for damage.</p>

      <p>A condition note on any items that are at risk: high-value ornaments, fragile furniture, specialised finishes. A short note in your phone or in an email to yourself dated before the first open home is enough.</p>

      <p>Confirmation that the agent has the sign-in sheet, two staff scheduled for the inspection, and a clear plan for hazard management at the entry. A two-minute conversation before the first open home is enough. The agent has done this hundreds of times. They will not be offended by the question and will appreciate that the seller is engaged.</p>

      <p>Insurance confirmation: a current contents policy with accidental damage cover, a buildings policy with public liability cover, and contact details for both insurers stored somewhere accessible. If a claim ever needs to be made, having the policy numbers and contact details ready makes the process faster and the outcome more reliable.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agent's role in managing risk</h2>

      <p>An experienced Brisbane agent runs the open home as a risk-managed event, not just a marketing event. The behaviours to expect from a professional team are practical.</p>

      <p>Two staff present at any active open home. One signing visitors in at the entry, one moving through the home maintaining line of sight. The second staff member is also the person who notices a wet entry tile, an unsupervised child near a fragile item, or a visitor heading for a hazard area.</p>

      <p>Hazard awareness as part of the pre-inspection setup. The agent should walk the home before the open home opens and identify anything that has changed since the previous inspection, particularly wet floors, displaced furniture or items moved during cleaning.</p>

      <p>Clear management of children at the inspection. A young child wandering unsupervised is the highest-frequency risk scenario for both damage and injury. An experienced agent will politely engage parents and offer to keep children near the entry while the parents inspect, or at least make clear that the agent has noticed and is paying attention.</p>

      <p>Sign-in records that include contact details. A reliable sign-in record is the difference between a recoverable damage incident and an unrecoverable one. If a visitor knocks over a vase and leaves quickly, the contact details on the sign-in are the only practical path to a conversation about the damage.</p>

      <p>An incident report habit. A good agent reports any damage observed during the inspection at the end of the open home, not three days later. That conversation lets the seller make the insurance decision while the evidence is fresh.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When something does go wrong</h2>

      <p>Most campaigns produce one or two minor incidents and no major ones. If something significant does happen, the steps are the same whether it is a damaged item or a visitor injury.</p>

      <p>Document the incident immediately. Photographs of the damage or the hazard, the date and time, the contact details of any visitor involved, and a short written note while the detail is fresh. If a visitor injury has occurred, the visitor's contact details and any account of what happened from the agent's perspective are essential.</p>

      <p>Notify your insurer the same day. Both contents accidental-damage claims and public liability claims work better when the report is prompt. Insurers are not surprised by open-home claims; they are common enough that the process is well established.</p>

      <p>Talk to the agent about the sign-in records and any CCTV footage. If the incident involves a specific visitor, the sign-in sheet may identify who was on site at the time. If your home has entry CCTV, the footage should be saved while it is still on the device.</p>

      <p>If the incident is a visitor injury that may lead to a claim, do not attempt to handle it directly with the visitor. The right path is to notify your insurer, let the public liability section of your policy manage the conversation, and provide the visitor with a contact path through the insurer. Admissions of fault made directly to an injured visitor before the insurer has been engaged can complicate the claim.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The campaign-budget context</h2>

      <p>Most of the steps in this article cost very little in money and not much in time. Adding accidental damage to a contents policy for the campaign duration is typically a small premium increase. Frosted-glass dots, contrast tape on steps and a few signs cost a small amount of cash and an afternoon of effort. Moving fragile items off side tables and into a cupboard for four weeks is free.</p>

      <p>The point of doing the work is not that something is likely to go wrong. The point is that the cost of preparing is low and the cost of an incident with no preparation is high enough that the comparison is not close. A seller who has thought about damage and liability before the first open home is also a seller who has thought about visitor flow, agent supervision, pet management and security, which are all the same set of habits.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical takeaway</h2>

      <p>Open-home damage is more common than theft. Visitor injuries are rare but real. Both are managed with the same set of habits: a walkthrough of the property before the first inspection, a short conversation with the agent, accidental damage cover added to the contents policy, and a clear documentation routine. The investment is small. The reduction in stress across a four-week campaign is large.</p>

      <p>Sellers who run their open homes with this framework in place tend to enjoy the campaign more, communicate better with their agent, and end up with a cleaner result. The risk profile is genuinely small once the preparation is done, and the home stays presentable for the full campaign rather than wearing down across consecutive busy weekends.</p>

